This is a raw draft of a possible solution for #25050.

The idea is to get rid of 1500+ lines of code and delete all `emitInsSize*` functions with complex logic and reuse the same mechanism that generates real instruction bytes to get the precise instruction sizes where we need them.

The main problem is that `emitOutputInstr` doesn't only emit instruction bytes, it also:
1. emits relocations via `emitRecordRelocation` where the first argument is the final address, the others can be memorized;

2. updates GC info via `emitGCregLiveUpd` and similar functions, also can be memorized;

I was trying to memorize that during the first pass but hit an issue that described in https://github.com/dotnet/coreclr/issues/23006#issuecomment-517485469 and stooped that experiment for now.

Another problem is that throughput could regress, we are calculating more that we need on the first pass and because we can't memorize it (without additional work) we duplicate this work again during the second pass. I have not measured TP yet.

The advantages are:
1. better predictions, but the size of the saved code is small, less than 1%;
2. won't need to support both code paths and duplicate work, as was done for HW intrinsics and led to asserts and bugs;

I need the idea review to understand if we want to move in this direction or can work on a better solution for this issue (preferably a one, that doesn't require rewriting emitter from scratch).

